WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.289
Let's version your repositories like code!

00:00:03.289 --> 00:00:04.815
We'll freeze a checkpoint,

00:00:04.815 --> 00:00:06.342
give it a name,

00:00:06.342 --> 00:00:08.631
then drop a real database table.

00:00:08.631 --> 00:00:11.302
The rollback brings back the exact frozen

00:00:11.302 --> 00:00:11.683
state,

00:00:11.683 --> 00:00:12.828
every row included,

00:00:12.828 --> 00:00:13.591
in seconds.

00:00:14.362 --> 00:00:15.918
The model is git,

00:00:15.918 --> 00:00:17.474
but for whole repositories.

00:00:17.474 --> 00:00:19.420
A commit is a frozen,

00:00:19.420 --> 00:00:20.198
immutable image.

00:00:20.198 --> 00:00:22.143
It refuses to even mount,

00:00:22.143 --> 00:00:24.477
so nothing can ever change it.

00:00:24.477 --> 00:00:27.201
A branch is just a name pointing

00:00:27.201 --> 00:00:28.368
at a commit.

00:00:28.368 --> 00:00:31.091
And checkout turns any commit back into

00:00:31.091 --> 00:00:31.870
a fresh,

00:00:31.870 --> 00:00:32.648
writable fork.

00:00:35.913 --> 00:00:38.538
Our working fork holds version one of the app

00:00:38.538 --> 00:00:41.164
state — a simple marker file makes it visible.

00:00:45.116 --> 00:00:46.174
Version one,

00:00:46.174 --> 00:00:47.232
on disk.

00:00:50.526 --> 00:00:52.469
It is not just files.

00:00:52.469 --> 00:00:55.189
A real PostgreSQL database lives in this

00:00:55.189 --> 00:00:55.966
fork too,

00:00:55.966 --> 00:00:58.686
and the customers table holds three rows.

00:00:58.686 --> 00:00:59.852
Remember that number.

00:01:02.352 --> 00:01:03.012
Three rows.

00:01:03.012 --> 00:01:05.653
That's the data we're about to put in

00:01:05.653 --> 00:01:05.983
danger.

00:01:09.304 --> 00:01:10.101
Freeze it.

00:01:10.101 --> 00:01:12.889
The commit captures the entire repository as

00:01:12.889 --> 00:01:14.084
an immutable image,

00:01:14.084 --> 00:01:15.280
with a message,

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:16.076
an author,

00:01:16.076 --> 00:01:17.271
and a parent.

00:01:17.271 --> 00:01:18.466
Exactly like git,

00:01:18.466 --> 00:01:19.662
but for everything,

00:01:19.662 --> 00:01:20.458
database included.

00:01:23.458 --> 00:01:23.919
Committed.

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:26.223
This snapshot can never change.

00:01:26.223 --> 00:01:28.526
It refuses to even mount.

00:01:31.855 --> 00:01:33.312
Give the commit a name.

00:01:33.312 --> 00:01:35.643
The stable branch now points at version one.

00:01:36.718 --> 00:01:38.834
A branch is a name you can come back to.

00:01:42.101 --> 00:01:42.885
Keep working.

00:01:42.885 --> 00:01:45.628
Version two replaces version one in the

00:01:45.628 --> 00:01:46.411
working fork.

00:01:46.411 --> 00:01:48.370
The commit does not care.

00:01:51.319 --> 00:01:52.858
The working fork moved on.

00:01:52.858 --> 00:01:54.088
The history did not.

00:01:57.364 --> 00:01:58.583
Now the disaster.

00:01:58.583 --> 00:02:01.426
The risky change drops the customers table.

00:02:01.426 --> 00:02:04.269
In real life this is the moment

00:02:04.269 --> 00:02:05.488
your stomach sinks.

00:02:07.424 --> 00:02:08.307
Drop table ran.

00:02:08.307 --> 00:02:10.663
The data is gone from the working fork.

00:02:13.931 --> 00:02:16.437
Ask for the rows again and the

00:02:16.437 --> 00:02:17.870
database says it straight:

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:19.660
relation customers does not exist.

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:21.093
The disaster is real.

00:02:21.093 --> 00:02:22.525
Every row is gone.

00:02:25.444 --> 00:02:27.982
Relation does not exist.

00:02:27.982 --> 00:02:29.251
Three rows,

00:02:29.251 --> 00:02:29.885
gone.

00:02:33.166 --> 00:02:35.236
Commit the risky change too,

00:02:35.236 --> 00:02:36.892
broken table and all.

00:02:36.892 --> 00:02:38.962
History records what actually happened.

00:02:38.962 --> 00:02:40.204
Two commits now,

00:02:40.204 --> 00:02:41.446
parent and child.

00:02:44.446 --> 00:02:46.092
Two snapshots in the chain.

00:02:49.366 --> 00:02:51.408
And there is the history:

00:02:51.408 --> 00:02:53.042
version two on top,

00:02:53.042 --> 00:02:54.676
version one below it,

00:02:54.676 --> 00:02:56.309
messages and authors included,

00:02:56.309 --> 00:02:58.352
without unlocking a single image.

00:03:01.352 --> 00:03:02.537
A repo log,

00:03:02.537 --> 00:03:04.513
exactly like a git log.

00:03:07.823 --> 00:03:09.167
Now the payoff.

00:03:09.167 --> 00:03:11.857
Check the stable branch out into

00:03:11.857 --> 00:03:14.098
a brand new writable fork.

00:03:14.098 --> 00:03:14.994
Reflink clone:

00:03:14.994 --> 00:03:15.442
near-instant,

00:03:15.442 --> 00:03:16.339
any size.

00:03:19.339 --> 00:03:21.759
A writable copy of the frozen version one,

00:03:21.759 --> 00:03:22.970
in about a second.

00:03:26.301 --> 00:03:28.652
Start the rollback fork like any other repo.

00:03:36.828 --> 00:03:37.925
Two forks running:

00:03:37.925 --> 00:03:39.754
today's version and the checkpoint.

00:03:43.026 --> 00:03:44.244
And the proof:

00:03:44.244 --> 00:03:46.682
the rollback fork reads version one.

00:03:46.682 --> 00:03:49.525
The working fork still has version two.

00:03:49.525 --> 00:03:51.150
History you can run.

00:03:52.650 --> 00:03:53.518
Rollback complete.

00:03:53.518 --> 00:03:56.124
Nothing was overwritten to get here.

00:03:59.475 --> 00:04:01.424
And the part that matters most:

00:04:01.424 --> 00:04:03.049
the dropped table is back,

00:04:03.049 --> 00:04:04.674
all three rows of it.

00:04:04.674 --> 00:04:06.299
The rollback restored the database,

00:04:06.299 --> 00:04:07.599
not just the files.

00:04:10.993 --> 00:04:12.280
Three rows again.

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:13.997
The disaster is undone.

00:04:28.936 --> 00:04:30.180
Commits never change,

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:31.425
forks never wait.

00:04:31.425 --> 00:04:32.254
Next up,

00:04:32.254 --> 00:04:35.157
we move a whole running repository to

00:04:35.157 --> 00:04:35.986
another machine,

00:04:35.986 --> 00:04:36.401
live.

00:04:36.401 --> 00:04:38.889
See you in the next one!
